04263nam a22006375i 9780823291144DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20222007nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232911447 a10.1515/97808232911442doi  a(DE-B1597)566157  a(OCoLC)1306538137  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aHIS0360402bisacsh1 aKeller, Christian B., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aChancellorsville and the Germans :bNativism, Ethnicity, and Civil War Memory /cChristian B. Keller. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2022] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (238 p.) :b20 Illustrations, black and white  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe North's Civil War00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tMaps -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1 German Americans, Know Nothings, and the Outbreak of the War -- t2 Before Chancellorsville: Sigel, Blenker, and the Reinforcement of German Ethnicity in the Union Army, 1861–1862 -- t3 The Battle of Chancellorsville and the German Regiments of the Eleventh Corps -- t4 ‘‘Retreating and Cowardly Poltroons’’: The Anglo American Reaction -- t5 ‘‘All We Ask Is Justice’’: The Germans Respond -- t6 Nativism and German Ethnicity after Chancellorsville -- t7 Chancellorsville and the Civil War in German American Memory -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOften called Lee’s greatest triumph, the battle of Chancellorsville decimated the Union Eleventh Corps, composed of large numbers of German-speaking volunteers. Poorly deployed, the unit was routed by “Stonewall” Jackson and became the scapegoat for the Northern defeat, blamed by many on the “flight” of German immigrant troops. The impact on America’s large German community was devastating. But there is much more to the story than that. Drawing for the first time on German-language newspapers, soldiers’ letters, memoirs, and regimental records, Christian Keller reconstructs the battle and its aftermath from the German-American perspective, military and civilian. He offers a fascinating window into a misunderstood past, one where the German soldiers’ valor has been either minimized or dismissed as cowardly. He critically analyzes the performance of the German regiments and documents the impact of nativism on Anglo-American and German-American reactions—and on German self-perceptions as patriots and Americans. For German-Americans, the ghost of Chancellorsville lingered long, and Keller traces its effects not only on ethnic identity, but also on the dynamics of inclusion and assimilation in American life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 7aHISTORY / United States / 19th Century.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831107072980 cprintz978082322651140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082329114440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823291144423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823291144/original  a978-3-11-070729-8  Fordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK